The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Couple seek SC protection
                                                                                                               Couple seek SC protection
          SAMANWAYA RAUTRAY                              
	New Delhi, March 5: The Supreme Court will tomorrow hear a runaway couples appeal seeking police protection from the wifes family.        
	Arunendra Narayan, 28, has also alleged that his brother-in-law Kulbhushan Jain had shot at his mother and sisters, injuring them seriously.        
	Arunendra, who is from Uttar Pradesh, and 29-year-old Ruchi Jain, from Madhya Pradesh, had met in the capital. Arunendra is pursuing a PhD in social medicine and community health in Delhi.        
	When Ruchis conservative Jain family got wind of the affair  Arunendra is from an Other Backward Class  she was locked up during a visit to her Muraina home. Her father Narendra and brother Kulbhushan allegedly beat her up.        
	Arunendra got an NGO to move court and Ruchi was freed. They married according to Arya Samaj rites on February 29 and started living in a Delhi neighbourhood.         
	Ruchi informed her family about the wedding and the response was a warning of a bloodbath. Days later, Arunendras mother Kamala was shot thrice in the stomach in Allahabad. She is battling for life as is Archana, his 25-year-old sister, who was shot thrice in the back. Anushri, another sister, too, was seriously wounded, the petition added.                                                                                                                                                                            
